<DOC><DOCNO> AP890531-0192 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2330EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Afghan-Shiites     05-31 0182</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Afghan-Shiites,0187</SECOND><HEAD>Shiite Negotiations With Interim Guerrilla Government Deadlocked</HEAD><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three days of negotiations on a sharein the Afghan guerrilla government for minority Shiite Moslemsended in deadlock Wednesday, but the main Shiite leader said moretalks would be held.   Karim Khalili, leader of the eight Afghan guerrilla groups basedin Iran, said a six-member commission had been formed to maintaincontact between his alliance and guerrilla leaders headquartered inPakistan.   Khalili and the Shiite minority want seven Cabinet posts in theprovisional government and have been offered four. They also demandrepresentation on a council controlled by leaders of theseven-party coalition based in Pakistan.   About 15 percent of Afghanistan's people are Shiites, and therest follow the main Sunni sect of Islam.   The guerrillas present the provisional government as analternative to the Soviet-sponsored Marxist regime in Kabul.   Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in April1978 and Soviet soldiers entered country in December 1979. Anestimated 115,000 were in Afghanistan when the Red Army began itswithdrawal, which was completed Feb. 15.</TEXT></DOC>